No, I don’t think you typed the command wrong. This part looks right:

podman run --rm --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test all

The issue is most likely inside the image, not your command.

Based on your Dockerfile, the file should exist because you added:

COPY tests/ /usr/local/share/aerolit-pxe-content/tests/
RUN chmod 0755 /entrypoint.sh /usr/local/bin/generate-pxe-content.py \
    && chmod 0755 /usr/local/share/aerolit-pxe-content/tests/*.sh \
    && chmod 0755 /usr/local/share/aerolit-pxe-content/tests/pxe-content-test \
    && ln -sf /usr/local/share/aerolit-pxe-content/tests/pxe-content-test /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test

The most likely problem is this:

#!/usr/bin/env bash

Your image is based on an Alpine-style image, and it probably does not have bash installed. When a script exists but its shebang points to a missing interpreter, Linux often reports it as:

No such file or directory

Run this to confirm:

podman run --rm --entrypoint /bin/sh registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test -lc '
set -e
ls -l /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test
ls -l /usr/local/share/aerolit-pxe-content/tests/
head -1 /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test | cat -A
command -v bash || true
command -v env || true
'

If you see the script exists, but command -v bash prints nothing, that is the problem.

The easiest fix is to install bash in the image. Add this near the top of the Dockerfile after the Python check, before the COPY tests/ lines:

RUN command -v bash >/dev/null 2>&1 || apk add --no-cache bash

So this section would become roughly:

RUN command -v python3 >/dev/null 2>&1 || \
    (echo "ERROR: base image must include python3." >&2 && exit 1)
RUN command -v bash >/dev/null 2>&1 || apk add --no-cache bash
COPY templates/ /templates/
COPY content/boot.ipxe.tmpl /templates/boot.ipxe.tmpl
COPY content/ui/ /etc/nginx/html/ui/
COPY nginx/pxe.conf /etc/nginx/conf.d/default.conf
COPY nginx/pxe.conf /etc/nginx/http.d/default.conf
COPY scripts/generate-pxe-content.py /usr/local/bin/generate-pxe-content.py
COPY entrypoint.sh /entrypoint.sh
COPY content/profiles/ /profiles/
COPY tests/ /usr/local/share/aerolit-pxe-content/tests/
RUN chmod 0755 /entrypoint.sh /usr/local/bin/generate-pxe-content.py \
    && chmod 0755 /usr/local/share/aerolit-pxe-content/tests/*.sh \
    && chmod 0755 /usr/local/share/aerolit-pxe-content/tests/pxe-content-test \
    && ln -sf /usr/local/share/aerolit-pxe-content/tests/pxe-content-test /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test

Then rebuild/push the test image and run:

podman run --rm --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test all

One more thing to check: make sure tests/pxe-content-test itself does not have Windows line endings. This command will show it:

podman run --rm --entrypoint /bin/sh registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test -lc '
head -1 /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test | cat -A
'

Good output:

#!/usr/bin/env bash$

Bad output:

#!/usr/bin/env bash^M$

If you see ^M, run this in the repo before rebuilding:

sed -i 's/\r$//' tests/pxe-content-test tests/*.sh

So: your command is fine. I’d fix the Dockerfile by installing bash, rebuild the test image, and rerun the same command.